title: Truly Madly Guilty
author: Moriarty, Liane*
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: This is the third book by Liane Moriarty I read (in a row, no less) and by now I can say that her novels are reliably well written and reliably well cThis is the third book by Liane Moriarty I read (in a row, no less) and by now I can say that her novels are reliably well written and reliably well constructed. The characters feel reliably sympathetic and realistic in their ups and downs. This is pleasurable reading material.In this one, Moriarty tries some new things by dipping her toe into issues of class (a little bit) and mental health (slightly more). We have three couples, the fairly regular Clementine and Sam, the socially awkward, traumatized-by-their-upbringing Erika and Oliver, and the not-quite-belonging-to-the-same-suburban-class-as-the-others Tiffany and Vid (who are seen as nouveaux riches and a little gauche).  And they all take part in the Fateful Barbecue."Six responsible adults. Three cute kids. One small dog. It’s just a normal weekend. What could possibly go wrong?" goes the description. And about 60% of the book is a slow buildup to what has gone wrong. Unfortunately, this is where the narration doesn't quite stand to the task. The chapters more or less alternate between the present (two months later) and the Fateful Day. The characters are traumatised by the event and think/speak about it only in oblique terms. "What if we didn't go?" "What if it never happened?" is a common refrain. The refrain of plot contrivance, as it turns out. The problem is that everyone in the book knows what happened, but the author chooses to withhold it from the reader - which, quite frankly, is just dishonest. For a moment you wonder, maybe the characters don't remember the events exactly and the book will be about reconstructing their memories of the day (which would validate the premise) - but nope. They remember. They're just not telling.So you wonder - what is so terrible that they don't want to talk about it? Did someone die? Was someone permanently injured? Did they accidentally barbecue one of the kids? Or maybe it wasn't terrible, just shameful? DID THEY HAVE A HUGE ORGY? (view spoiler)[Nah. One of the kids got into the fountain, wasn't breathing for a minute, but they saved her with expertly administered CPR. She's completely fine in the present. (hide spoiler)]My point isn't that the idea itself is not interesting, but, rather, that the story could be just as engrossing if the major point of suspense wasn't "what happened" but "how it happened precisely" or "who was responsible". And Moriarty has the chops to write it! But instead, the narrative cannot but result in an anticlimactic reveal.And there is also a tertiary story concerning a grumpy neighbour, (view spoiler)[which just didn't work for me, because the characters never figure out that their barbecque antics were to blame for the neighbour's death, and they draw no conclusions from it. So the neighbour's tied into the story with some coincidences, but his plot could easily be extracted and the book would not be poorer for it.  (hide spoiler)]Still, I want to emphasise that it is a good reading and overall enjoyable - it's just that, frustratingly, a few different writing choices would have made the book so much better......more

On one level, it seemI had actually been super excited for this book - I thought it would be right up my alley. And it kinda was, but it also wasn't. On one level, it seemed like it could have been my favourite Kate Elliott book ever (warrior princesses and space opera and queerness, oh my!), but then... it didn't quite grab me the way I thought it would. For me, the problem was that (1) I wasn't sure why I should care for those people - for a looong time, the book doesn't give the reader enough to be invested in the characters and (2) that the action scenes just wouldn't stop. I mean, I understand, space opera, evil plotting, war, we need action. And yet. Slow the pace, show us the characters, give us more meat on the setting, it will still work. (And my side quibble is that I didn't like the father, but I generally don't like the fathers in Elliott's books).I will definitely read book number two and I do think I will enjoy it more, because now I know how the world works and who to root for!...more

my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: I received an e-copy of this book from the publisher via NetGalley for  purposes.I actually finished this book over a month ago, but I'm still nI received an e-copy of this book from the publisher via NetGalley for  purposes.I actually finished this book over a month ago, but I'm still not quite sure how to  it. I had previously read Sarah Pinsker's short story collections, which I mostly loved - the writing, the language - save for one story. The one on which this novel is based.This is perhaps a little disingenuous, because I didn't dislike that story. I just thought it was the least exciting of the bunch, because... I'm not huge on reading about music and musicians and how music is made and about live performances (unless it's non-fiction, but even then, not in every case). And, welp, this is my problem with A Song for a New Day: it's a book about musicians and live performances and (to a lesser degree) music industry in a world that has survived a smallpox pandemic, and where most human interactions have moved to virtual reality. On the plus side, the writing is very good - I really enjoy Pinsker's way with language, her sensitivity - and the worldbuilding is compelling (especially given Covid). Unfortunately, in addition to all the music (and YMMV, maybe other readers will love that), the plot gets didactic in a pretty annoying way. Capitalism is BAD and big corporations are only out to get your money - oh, of course, but there's surely a way to write about it that doesn't make the reader feel like she was repeatedly hit over the head with the message.Overall, I will be on the lookout for Pinsker's future works - I do have high hopes for her. It's just that this one wasn't exactly my cup of tea....more

review: So this  is written after reading 20 BSC books.I actually read the first three Baby-Sitters Club books back when I was a wee sprog, perhaps 7 orSo this  is written after reading 20 BSC books.I actually read the first three Baby-Sitters Club books back when I was a wee sprog, perhaps 7 or 8 years old. In many ways, I think these are perfect books for that age, and I would have loved having all 130 (or however many had been published by that time) to read then. One thing, though, is that when I was 7 or 8, I thought that the protagonists of BSC were so adult and responsible. Clearly, much much older than me.They were 12.But in some way, that feeling stuck with me, and even now, reading the following books, I often feel like I'm reading about 16-year-olds at least. And then I get this weird dissonance from their having to get home early from their sitting jobs, and I remember - 12. So now I read the first 21 BSC books - mostly due to the Netflix series having come out. And I still think they are very nice reading. Sure, they are formulaic and get repetitive, but there is some fun stuff: focus on friendship, focus on overcoming difficulties (together with your friend group, or on your own). The "mystery" books are pretty fun (Claudia and the Phone Phantom, Dawn and the Haunted House). And you basically read them in one afternoon*, which is also nice. Good summer reading, especially when you have some nostalgia for the series. (* Or three in a day, as it were.) What is weird: (1)that 12-year-olds in the books are so into boys and having boyfriends. You are 12! You have plenty of time to get coupled up! It's NOT strange for kids your age not to be interested in dating! (Yeah, having first crushes, sure, but somehow Kristy's lack of interest in boys is "babyish". No, it's not!) (2) that diabetes is treated like it were an STD - super shameful and strange. It was strange when I read it first, it remains strange now. The last book I read was the one where Kristy starts a softball league and... sorry, nope. That's it for me. I can deal with babysitting and strict parents and family conflicts and issues with friends and stepfamilies and so on, but sports give me the zzz. So that's it for me.But it gives me a lot of satisfaction that I finally got to read the 4th and the 5th volume, actually!  They had been teased in the back of the Polish vol. 3 all those years ago and they never got published in Poland, which, as my wife aptly realised, means that we got books for three out of four core friends. And that's how I learned what betrayal was when it came to books never being published although you you hoped for them....more

my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: I am a huge Tori Amos fan. And so, there was no question that I would read this book. On release.Having said that, I'm... not entirely sure how to judI am a huge Tori Amos fan. And so, there was no question that I would read this book. On release.Having said that, I'm... not entirely sure how to judge it. (I'm still not quite sure what I think about her first book, Piece by Piece, released in 2005, at the height of my fandom.) There are personal stories. There are personal stories concerning politics. (She never invokes the "personal is political" idea, but she might as well do.) There are stories about how politics and things going on in the world influence the creation of stories. It is not a clearly shaped, coherent narrative, but, rather, a collection of personal reflections. What Amos advises is, in short, to "out-create": respond to the political crisis with creativity. Be resistant by being creative. It's an engaging book, but I'm not entirely sure that it is for everybody....more
